[2026-06-24]
## RR Day 40 — paste and join Commands

### Completed
- Combined two files side by side with paste
- Identified tab as paste's default delimiter using cat -A
- Used -d flag to replace default delimiter with comma
- Piped paste output into awk with matching -F delimiter
- Used join to match files on a shared key field (IP address)
- Proved join drops unmatched rows — inner join behavior
- Proved paste blindly zips by position regardless of content
- Built a full Network Status Report using join + awk BEGIN/END

### Key Concepts
- paste = dumb and positional — zips lines by position, no matching
- join = smart — only outputs rows where the key exists in both files
- paste default delimiter is tab (^I), not space — must match in awk with -F'\t'
- -d flag overrides paste's default delimiter
- awk never errors on missing fields — prints empty silently, dangerous
- Getting correct output for the wrong reason is the most dangerous kind of working
- join default separator is space — matches awk's default, no -F needed
- Fields = columns, rows = lines — two different things

