[2026-06-21]
## RR Day 38 — sed In-Place Editing and Backups

### Completed
- Reviewed -i flag risk: edits file directly, can overwrite
  if pattern is wrong — no undo
- Safe pattern 1: redirect to a new file with >
  sed 's/old/new/' file.txt > file_new.txt
- Safe pattern 2: let sed make the backup automatically
  sed -i.bak 's/old/new/' file.txt
- Confirmed .bak preserves the original before overwriting
- Multiple substitutions in one pass with -e:
  sed -e 's/down/up/' -e 's/stopped/running/' status.txt
- Line-specific replacement — only act on line N:
  sed '3s/error/OK/' log.txt
- Range replacement — act on a span of lines:
  sed '1,5s/WARNING/NOTICE/' log.txt

### Key Concepts
- -i = in-place, modifies the file directly with no
  screen output
- -i.bak = in-place WITH a safety backup — always use
  this form in production
- Without a line number, sed applies the substitution to
  EVERY matching line in the file
- Prefixing with a line number or range (3s, 1,5s) scopes
  the change to just those lines
- -e chains multiple edits in a single command instead of
  piping sed into sed
- Default sed only swaps the FIRST match per line; add the
  g flag (s/old/new/g) to replace all matches on the line

