## Day 30: Parsing Logs with Extended Regex

### Completed & Concepts Locked In
- Built a 3-stage log extraction pipeline from scratch:
  `journalctl -u sshd | grep -v '0.0.0.0' | grep -oE
  '[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}\.[0-9]{1,3}'`
- Stage 1: Pull SSH journal logs.
- Stage 2: -v excludes noise (0.0.0.0 — server listening address).
- Stage 3: -oE extracts only IP addresses using extended regex.
- Key concepts: -v inverts match (excludes), -o extracts match only,
  -E enables extended regex unlocking {n,m} and + and ?,
  \. means literal dot (unescaped dot = any character),
  without -E curly braces are treated as literal characters
  so the pattern returns nothing.
- Built every piece of the pipeline independently through
  reasoning — not copying.

