[2026-06-04]
## Day 29: Regex Character Classes Against /etc/passwd

### Completed & Concepts Locked In
- Ran three regex extractions against live /etc/passwd file:
  1. `grep -E '^[a-z_][a-z0-9_-]*'` — matched all usernames at
     start of line. Too broad — matched every line (false positive lesson).
  2. `grep -oE '/[a-z/]+sh$'` — extracted only real login shells.
     `$` anchor meant only lines ending in sh survived. Only /bin/bash returned.
  3. `grep -oE '/home/[a-z_]+'` — extracted home directories.
     Only /home/sensei returned — confirming one real interactive user.
- Key concepts: `^` anchors to start of line, `$` anchors to end,
  `-o` returns only the matched portion not the whole line,
  character classes `[a-z_]` match one character from a defined set.
- Security observation: running shell audit on /etc/passwd shows
  which accounts have real access vs system accounts using nologin.

